In article <9409142114333861@wov.com>,
John Dehaven <john.dehaven@wov.com> wrote:
> TK> Apparently you are unaware that the RSAREF library which is used
> TK> in PGP 2.6 is not as efficient, or as fast, as the code used in 2.3a.
> TK> It is CLEARLY in PKP's interests to make the FREE version less
> TK> desirable.
>
>I have heard this claim a lot.  So I did some measurements.
>There is no clear difference in speed--in fact if anything the
>RSAREF lib might be a tad faster under some conditions, but it
>is really all buried in other larger variances, really, so I
>would not swear to that either.  I don't believe there is any
>*practical* difference at all.  (BTW, I don't know what
>"efficient" might mean if not speed.  Memory usage?  Didn't
>measure that, but neither gave me any trouble.)

The bignum arithmetic code that comes with the RSAREF library
is very slow.  However, the RSAREF license permits modifying
the library in order to make it run faster.  MIT PGP 2.6 does
this by making RSAREF call the old PGP MPI arithmetic library.
Thus, the speed should be about the same.
